"1587","1575":"1575","5 February 1572":"5. februar 1572","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1573":"1573","20Mar1573":"20. marts 1573","1549":"1549","Pontesbury,Shropshire,England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Pontesbury, Shrops, Engand":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","Pontesbury, Shropshire, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","Pontesbury, Shrops, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1546–":"1546–Overleden","1550–1579":"1550–1579","1573–Male":"1573–Overleden","1575–1676":"1575–1676","1578–1578":"1578–1578","1579–Female":"1579–Overleden","1546–Male":"1546–Overleden","21 Jun 1579":"21 juni 1579","03 APR 1578":"3 april 1578","1550":"1550","15 March 1575":"15 maart 1575","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1579":"1579","1578":"1578","1676":"1676","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","5 February 1572":"5 februari 1572","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1573":"1573","20Mar1573":"20 maart 1573","1549":"1549","Pontesbury,Shropshire,England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pontesbury, Shrops, Engand":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","Pontesbury, Shropshire, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","Pontesbury, Shrops, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1546–":"1546–Deceased","1550–1579":"1550–1579","1573–Male":"1573–Deceased","1575–1676":"1575–1676","1578–1578":"1578–1578","1579–Female":"1579–Deceased","1546–Male":"1546–Deceased","21 Jun 1579":"21 June 1579","03 APR 1578":"3 April 1578","1550":"1550","15 March 1575":"15 March 1575","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1579":"1579","1578":"1578","1676":"1676","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","5 February 1572":"5 February 1572","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1573":"1573","20Mar1573":"20 March 1573","1549":"1549","Pontesbury,Shropshire,England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Pontesbury, Shrops, Engand":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","Pontesbury, Shropshire, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","Pontesbury, Shrops, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rogers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Roger  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b> (see   Rorie  ).","History: Thomas Rogers (<i>c.</i> 1587–1621), born in London, England, was among the Pilgrim Fathers who sailed on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He died during the first winter at Plymouth Colony, but his son Joseph survived and married, and was later joined in MA by his brother John. This name was subsequently brought to North America independently by many different bearers."],"variants":[{"name":"Roger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philippe, Alcee, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Rodgers","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Rogers  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":3,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":12,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":39,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":41,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":74,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":96,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Rogers was born in 1546, in Pontesbury, Shropshire, England. He married Anna Tilsley on 5 February 1572, in Pontesbury, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters."},"et":{"1546–":"1546–Surnud","1550–1579":"1550–